Plain — Examples
Nerijus Ramanauskas <nerijus@signaintermedia.com>


COMMENTS AND WHITESPACE

    ` Backtick starts a comment, ends at the line break.

    Whitespace and commas are interchangeable separators. These are the same:

        add 1, 2
        add 1 2


LITERALS

    ` Booleans
    yes
    no

    ` Nil
    none

    ` Integers
    42
    -7

    ` Reals
    3.14
    1.5e10

    ` Strings (single or double quotes, backslash escapes)
    "hello, world"
    'it\'s fine'


VARIABLES

    ` Assign with =
    x = 42;
    name = "Plain"

    ` Read a variable by using its name as an argument
    print x;
    print name


EXPRESSIONS

    ` Wrap any statement in [...] to use its result as a value
    print [add 1, 2];
    print [join "Hello, ", name, "!"];
    x = [multiply 6, 7]


ARITHMETIC

    ` Prefix form
    print [add 10, 3];         ` 13
    print [subtract 10, 3];    ` 7
    print [multiply 10, 3];    ` 30
    print [divide 10, 3];      ` 3
    print [modulo 10, 3]       ` 1

    ` Infix form — left side must be a named variable, not a literal
    x = 10;
    print [x + 3];             ` 13
    print [x - 3];             ` 7
    print [x * 3];             ` 30
    print [x / 3];             ` 3
    print [x % 3]              ` 1

    ` Reals promote automatically
    print [add 1, 0.5];        ` 1.5
    print [x + 0.5]            ` 10.5

    ` Infix is binary — chain via nesting for more than two operands
    print [add [x + 3] 2]      ` 15


COMPARISON

    x = 5;
    print [x = 5];               ` yes   (= means equality inside [...])
    print [x != 4];              ` yes
    print [x < 10];              ` yes
    print [x > 3];               ` yes
    print [x <= 5];              ` yes
    print [x >= 5]               ` yes

    ` The left operand must always be a named variable.
    ` To compare two literals, assign one to a variable first:
    `   a = "hello";
    `   print [a < "world"]    ` yes


LOGIC

    print [not yes]              ` no

    ` Prefix form — and/or accept multiple arguments
    print [and yes, yes];        ` yes
    print [or no, yes]           ` yes

    ` Infix and/or: left side must be a named variable
    a = yes;
    b = no;
    print [a and b];             ` no
    print [a or b]               ` yes

    ` Compound comparisons: nest expressions in prefix and/or
    x = 5;
    print [and [x > 0] [x < 10]];    ` yes
    print [or [x < 0] [x > 3]]       ` yes


STRINGS

    print [join "Hello, ", "world", "!"]    ` Hello, world!

    ` Numbers coerce to strings automatically
    print [join "Result: ", [add 1, 2]]     ` Result: 3


BLOCKS

    ` Curly braces create a deferred block — not evaluated until needed
    { print "I run when called" }

    ` Colon shorthand: opens a block, semicolon closes it
    : print "same thing";


IF

    x = 10;

    if [x > 5] {
        print "big"
    }

    ` With else
    if [x > 5] {
        print "positive"
    } else {
        print "not positive"
    }

    ` elseif — "else" followed by a condition (any non-block value) chains branches;
    ` "else" followed by a block is the final fallback
    x = 7;
    if [x > 10] { print "big" } else [x > 5] { print "medium" } else [x > 0] { print "small" } else { print "none" }

    ` Colon shorthand (no else)
    if [x = 10]: print "exactly ten";


REPEAT

    ` Infinite loop — use break to exit
    x = 0;
    repeat {
        x = [x + 1];
        if [x = 3]: break;
    };
    print x    ` 3

    ` Counted loop
    repeat 5 {
        print "hello"
    }

    ` Conditional loop — condition block is re-evaluated each iteration
    i = 0;
    repeat { i < 5 } {
        print i;
        i = [i + 1]
    }

    ` Counted loop with automatic variable binding
    repeat {i} times 5 {
        print i
    }
    ` Prints: 0, 1, 2, 3, 4

    ` The variable is scoped to the loop body
    repeat {x} times 3 {
        print x
    };
    ` x is not defined here — clean scope

    ` Nested counted loops
    repeat {y} times 3 {
        repeat {x} times 3 {
            print [join x ", " y]
        }
    }

    ` The modifier keyword "times" is extensible — future modifiers
    ` like "in", "till", "unless" can follow the same pattern


BREAK AND CONTINUE

    ` break exits the nearest repeat
    i = 0;
    repeat {
        if [i = 3]: break;
        print i;
        i = [i + 1]
    }
    ` Prints: 0, 1, 2

    ` continue skips to the next iteration
    i = 0;
    repeat { i < 6 } {
        i = [i + 1];
        if [equal [i % 2] 0]: continue;
        print i
    }
    ` Prints: 1, 3, 5


FUNCTIONS (immutable)

    ` Named form
    function square {n} {
        return [n * n]
    };

    print [square 5]    ` 25

    ` Expression form — [function {parameters} {body}] returns a callable value
    double = [function {n} { return [n * 2] }];
    print [double 5]    ` 10

    ` Functions cannot be reassigned after definition (immutable binding)


PROCEDURES (mutable)

    ` Named form
    procedure greet {name} {
        print [join "Hello, ", name, "!"]
    };

    greet "world"    ` Hello, world!

    ` Expression form — [procedure ...] returns a mutable, reassignable callable
    greet = [procedure {name} { print [join "Hey, ", name, "."] }];
    greet "Plain"    ` Hey, Plain.


RETURN

    function clamp {value, minimum, maximum} {
        if [value < minimum]: return minimum;
        if [value > maximum]: return maximum;
        return value
    };

    print [clamp 5, 0, 10];      ` 5
    print [clamp -3, 0, 10];     ` 0
    print [clamp 99, 0, 10]      ` 10


NESTED EXPRESSIONS

    function square {n} { return [n * n] };

    ` Nest expressions freely
    print [add [square 3] [square 4]]    ` 25

    ` Fibonacci
    function fibonacci {n} {
        if [n < 2]: return n;
        return [add [fibonacci [n - 1]] [fibonacci [n - 2]]]
    };

    print [fibonacci 10]    ` 55


DO

    ` Executes a block in a fresh scope and returns its value.
    ` Variables created inside do not leak into the surrounding frame.

    result = [do { x = 6; y = 7; return [x * y] }];
    print result    ` 42

    ` do is a regular mutable callable — it can be overridden or passed around
    print [type do]    ` callable


CLOSURES

    ` Functions and procedures capture their definition frame. Outer
    ` variables remain accessible and mutable even after the outer
    ` call returns.

    ` Counter factory — each counter has its own private state
    function make_counter {} {
        n = 0;
        return [procedure {} { n = [n + 1]; return n }]
    };

    counter = [make_counter];
    print [counter];    ` 1
    print [counter];    ` 2
    print [counter]     ` 3

    ` Partial application — capture a parameter as a closed-over variable
    function adder {n} {
        return [function {x} { return [x + n] }]
    };

    add5 = [adder 5];
    print [add5 3];     ` 8
    print [add5 10]     ` 15


LISTS

    ` Create a list with initial values
    items = [list 10, 20, 30];

    ` Access by index (zero-based)
    print [items get 0];       ` 10
    print [items get 2]        ` 30

    ` Modify an element
    items set 1, 99;
    print [items get 1]        ` 99

    ` Append and query length
    items append 42;
    print [items length]       ` 4

    ` Remove by index
    items remove 0;
    print [items get 0]        ` 99  (was 20→99, now first after 10 removed)

    ` Empty list
    empty = [list];
    print [empty length]       ` 0

    ` Use a flat list as a 2D grid (10 columns x 3 rows)
    grid = [list];
    repeat 30 { grid append 0 };

    ` Set cell (2, 1) to 5
    grid set [add [multiply 1 10] 2], 5;

    ` Get cell (2, 1)
    print [grid get [add [multiply 1 10] 2]]    ` 5

    ` Iterate over a list
    values = [list 1, 2, 3, 4, 5];
    i = 0;
    repeat [values length] {
        print [values get i];
        i = [i + 1]
    }


OBJECTS (C++ BRIDGE)

    ` The C++ host can register classes with bind_class<T>().
    ` Plain constructs objects and calls methods using bare keywords.

    ` Construct (calls the registered C++ constructor)
    v = [Vec2 3, 4];

    ` Call methods — the first bare keyword after the object is the method name
    print [v length];          ` 5
    print [v str];             ` Vec2(3, 4)

    ` Method with arguments
    w = [Vec2 1, 2];
    u = [v add w];
    print [u str]              ` Vec2(4, 6)

    ` Statement form (no return value needed)
    v draw

    ` If a method name collides with a bound variable, use a quoted string:
    length = 42;
    print [v "length"]         ` still calls the method, not the variable


TYPE INTROSPECTION

    print [type 42];       ` integer
    print [type 3.14];     ` real
    print [type "hello"];  ` string
    print [type yes];      ` boolean
    print [type none];     ` none

    fn = [function {x} { return x }];
    print [type fn]        ` callable


MULTIPLE STATEMENTS

    ` Semicolons separate statements on one line
    a = 1; b = 2; print [add a, b]    ` 3


FIRST-CLASS CALLABLES

    ` Built-in procedures are regular mutable bindings — store them, pass
    ` them as arguments, and invoke them exactly like user-defined callables.

    ` Store a built-in procedure in a variable
    branch = if;
    branch yes { print "yes" } { print "no" }    ` yes

    ` Pass a callable as an argument
    function apply {operation, a, b} {
        return [operation a, b]
    };

    print [apply add, 3, 4];         ` 7
    print [apply multiply, 3, 4];    ` 12

    ` Named comparison procedures — equal, less, greater — exist specifically
    ` for passing as first-class callables, since infix requires a named
    ` variable on the left and cannot be used in argument position directly.
    print [apply equal, 5, 5];       ` yes
    print [apply less, 3, 4];        ` yes
    print [apply greater, 4, 3]      ` yes

    ` Works with user-defined callables too
    function twice {f, x} {
        return [f [f x]]
    };

    double = [function {n} { return [n * 2] }];
    print [twice double, 3]    ` 12  (3 * 2 * 2)

    ` Override a built-in procedure — no keywords are reserved
    ` Use [procedure ...] so the override remains reassignable
    add = [procedure {a, b} { result = [a + 1]; return [result + b] }];
    print [add 2, 3];    ` 6

    add = [procedure {a, b} { return [a + b] }];
    print [add 2, 3]     ` 5


OPERATOR OVERRIDES

    ` Operators (+, -, *, /, %, <, >, <=, >=, !=, and, or) can be
    ` overridden just like any other procedure. A single override covers
    ` both infix [a + b] and prefix [+ a b] call sites.

    ` Named procedure form — operator as name
    procedure + {a, b} {
        return [multiply a b]
    };

    x = 10;
    print [x + 3];    ` 30  (infix)
    print [+ x 3]     ` 30  (prefix — same callable)

    ` Expression form — equivalent result
    + = [procedure {a, b} { return [multiply a b] }]

    ` Override comparison operators the same way
    procedure < {a, b} {
        return [greater a, b]    ` deliberately reversed
    };

    x = 3;
    print [x < 10]    ` no  (reversed: 3 is not greater than 10)

    ` Restore a default operator by redefining it
    + = [procedure {a, b} { return [add a b] }]


CLASSES AND OBJECTS

    ` Define a class with constructor parameters and methods.
    ` Methods defined with function are immutable; procedure are mutable.
    class Dog {name, age} {
        procedure bark {} {
            print [join name " says Woof!"]
        };
        function info {} {
            return [join name ", age: " age]
        };
        procedure rename {new_name} {
            name = new_name
        }
    };

    ` Create instances
    dog = [Dog "Rex", 3];
    dog bark;                ` Rex says Woof!
    print [dog info];        ` Rex, age: 3
    print [dog name];        ` Rex  (direct field access)
    print [type dog];        ` object

    ` Mutation through procedures
    dog rename "Buddy";
    dog bark;                ` Buddy says Woof!

    ` Multiple independent instances
    a = [Dog "Alpha", 1];
    b = [Dog "Beta", 2];
    a bark;                  ` Alpha says Woof!
    b bark                   ` Beta says Woof!

    ` Self-reference — methods can call other methods on the same instance
    class Calc {value} {
        function double {} { return [value * 2] };
        function quad {} { return [[self double] * 2] }
    };
    c = [Calc 5];
    print [c double];        ` 10
    print [c quad]           ` 20

    ` Anonymous class — returns a constructor callable
    Cat = [class {name} {
        function meow {} { return [join name " meows"] }
    }];
    cat = [Cat "Whiskers"];
    print [cat meow]         ` Whiskers meows

    ` Stateful object — counter pattern
    class Counter {} {
        count = 0;
        procedure increment {} { count = [count + 1] };
        function value {} { return count }
    };
    counter = [Counter];
    counter increment;
    counter increment;
    counter increment;
    print [counter value]    ` 3


KNOWN LIMITATIONS

    ` Infix requires the left operand to be a named variable.
    ` To compare a literal on the left, assign it to a variable first:
    `   a = "hello";
    `   print [a < "world"]    ` yes
    ` Or use equal/less/greater as first-class callables (see FIRST-CLASS CALLABLES).

    ` Infix is strictly binary. [a + b + c] only computes a + b.
    ` Chain arithmetic via nesting:
    `   [add [a + b] c]

    ` Compound conditions with infix and/or do not work as expected.
    ` [x > 0 and x < 10] only evaluates x > 0. Use prefix form:
    `   [and [x > 0] [x < 10]]

    ` function/procedure name {params} {body} only works when the name is
    ` not already bound as a non-operator variable. For rebinding a normal
    ` name, use the expression form:
    `   name = [procedure {params} {body}]
    ` Operator symbol names (+, -, etc.) are always safe to use in the
    ` named form regardless of whether they have been overridden before.
